<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-437-440  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 437 440.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MIS Week  April 30 1990 v11 n18 p29(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Split shifts. (managing project teams working on different shifts)(How do you manage when ...) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Roetzheim, William.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Many data processing departments are considering going to splitshifts as a means of increasing productivity by increasing staffwithout the need for corresponding increases in facilities andequipment.andP;  Managing project teams that extend across shifts ismore complicated than managing single shift projects.andP;  The needfor shifts to communicate requires an overlap in the shifts of atleast one hour, to be spent in communicating status, problems, andother up-to-the-minute information.andP;  Key personnel should adjusttheir schedules to straddle the two shifts.andP;  An electronic mailsystem for the recording of questions for answer by theappropriate person is a must.andP;  A voice-mail system can also bebeneficial.andP;  Creating a team spirit across shifts can be eased byhaving teams work together during the first week or so of theproject, by holding regular group meetings, and by providingcompany-sponsored group functions that are not directly related tothe project, such as field trips or group picnics.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Management StyleGuidelinesProject ManagementProductivity.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>